        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"724904\">rzeta0</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/113489-new-members/topic/struggling.20to.20find.20maths.20strategy.20to.20show.20inequality/near/470404072\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>my solution is so ugly! </p>\n<p>I realise I'm only a beginner but I do feel such exercises don't teach anything about lean concepts, and are merely algebra torture with not much educational value. </p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"724904\">@rzeta0</span> The \"algebra torture\" is probably necessary to discover a proof of this fact, but once you have done it in scratch work on paper, you don't need to write it out in Lean.  See the shorter <a href=\"#narrow/stream/116395-maths/topic/.E2.9C.94.20Mechanics.20of.20Proof.20Exercise.202.2E5.2E9.2E8/near/434636627\">outline here</a> for a hint.</p>",
        "id": 471560755,
        "sender_full_name": "Heather Macbeth",
        "timestamp": 1726778648
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I would describe the \"educational value\" of this problem as follows: often in proof-based maths, you (i.e., the author) can invent a proof which is very short and easy for someone else to read and check, at the cost of doing a ton of work behind the scenes yourself.</p>\n<p>This proof-writing style doesn't come naturally to most people: beginners tend to produce arguments like the <a href=\"#narrow/stream/113489-new-members/topic/struggling.20to.20find.20maths.20strategy.20to.20show.20inequality/near/470367373\">ones in your initial post</a>, which are easier to invent, but longer to read.</p>",
        "id": 471561551,
        "sender_full_name": "Heather Macbeth",
        "timestamp": 1726779015
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Anyway, this indeed doesn't \"teach anything about Lean concepts.\"  Instead, it's a lesson about maths itself (and in fact <em>Mechanics of Proof</em> is really intended as a maths textbook, and only incidentally as a Lean textbook.)</p>",
        "id": 471561703,
